ai-kv8.9:38.4_0: “Ānanda, as long as there’s a body, the intention that gives rise to bodily action causes pleasure and pain to arise in oneself.
ai-kv8.9:38.5_0: As long as there’s a voice, the intention that gives rise to verbal action causes pleasure and pain to arise in oneself.
ai-kv8.9:38.6_0: mind, the intention that gives rise to mental action causes pleasure and pain to arise in oneself.”
ai-kv8.9:39.4_0: “Mendicants, there are three kinds of bodily action that have unskillful intention, with suffering as their outcome and result.
ai-kv8.9:39.5_0: There are four kinds of verbal action that have unskillful intention, with suffering as their outcome and result.
ai-kv8.9:39.6_0: There are three kinds of mental action that have unskillful intention, with suffering as their outcome and result.
ai-kv8.9:39.7_0: There are three kinds of bodily action that have skillful intention, with happiness as their outcome and result.
ai-kv8.9:39.8_0: There are four kinds of successful verbal action that have skillful intention, with happiness as their outcome and result.
ai-kv8.9:39.9_0: There are three kinds of mental action that have skillful intention, with happiness as their outcome and result.”
ai-kv8.9:40.4_0: “Ānanda, if he were to answer, Samiddhi would answer:
ai-kv8.9:40.5_0: ‘After doing an intentional deed to be experienced as pleasant by way of body, speech, or mind, one feels pleasure.
ai-kv8.9:40.6_0: After doing an intentional deed to be experienced as painful by way of body, speech, or mind, one feels pain.
ai-kv8.9:40.7_0: Suppose a layman who has performed a deed to be experienced as neutral by way of body, speech, and mind, and develops a true goal of the wanderer Pāṭaliputta.”
ai-kv8.9:40.12_0: The discussion on form is finished.
